{"word":"μῖσος","slug":"μῖσος","sections":[{"paragraph":""},{"paragraph":""},{"paragraph":"<el><b>μῖσος</b></el> <el>(μῖσος, εος, τό,) </el><p/><i>hate, hatred</i>: and so,<p/><div class='li500'><b>I. </b><a href='S:passive signification'><a href='S:Passive Voice'>pass.</a></a> <i>hate borne</i> one, <i>a being hated</i>, <b><a href='S:Tragic, in Tragic Greek'>Trag.</a></b>, <b><a href='S:Plato'>Plat.</a></b><p/></div><div class='li750'><b>2. </b><a href='S:active signification'><a href='S:Active voice'>act.</a></a> <i>hate felt against</i> another, <i>a grudge</i>, <b><a href='S:Sophocles'>Soph.</a></b>, <a href='S:et cetera'>etc.</a>; <el>μ. τινός τινι</el> <i>felt by</i> one <i>against</i> another, <b><a href='S:Euripides'>Eur.</a></b><p/></div><div class='li500'><b>II. </b>of persons, <i>a hateful object</i>, = <a href='S:μίσημα'><el>μίσημα</el></a>, <b><a href='S:Tragic, in Tragic Greek'>Trag.</a></b><p/></div>"}]}